Acute promyelocytic leukemia in Crohn's disease. Case report and review of the literature.
 A 19-year-old man with a documented 2-year history of Crohn's disease abruptly developed leukopenia and thrombocytopenia.
 A diagnosis of acute promyelocytic leukemia was established by bone marrow cytology.
 Chromosomal analysis of bone marrow aspirate revealed aberrations of no.
 8 trisomy and translocation between no.
 15 and no.
 17 [46,XY,t(15q+,17q-)/47,XY,+8,t(15q+,17q-)].
 Nine cases of Crohn's disease complicated by leukemia have been reported, including the present one; once again, a relationship between Crohn's disease and leukemia is suggested.
